{{Infobox Shinto shrine | name = Kenkun Shrine | image = Kagura-den at Kenkun Jinja Spring 2010.JPG | width = 200px | caption = The [[Kagura|Kaguraden]] at Kenkun shrine | type = | dedication = [[Oda Nobunaga]] | founded = 1869 | closed = | founder = [[Emperor Meiji]] | priest = | address = | phone = 81-075-451-0170 | website = }}
{{nihongo|'''Kenkun Shrine'''|建勲神社,|''Kenkun-jinja''}} also known as '''Takeisao Shrine''', is a [[Shinto Shrine]] in the city of [[Kyoto]], [[Japan]].
==Funaoka Matsuri== The Funaoka Matsuri is a [[festival]] held every year on October 19th at Kenkun shrine commemorating the day when the diety, [[Oda Nobunaga]], first entered Kyoto in 1568. Young boys dressed in [[Middle Ages|medieval]] [[Armour|armor]] portray Nobunaga's army as they marched into Kyoto to take control of the government in the 1500s.<ref>{{Cite book| last1=Martin |first1=John H. |authorlink1= |last2=Martin |first2=Phyllis G. | title =Kyoto: A Cultural Guide | publisher =Tuttle Publishing | date =2002 | location =Singapore | pages =339 | url =http://books.google.com/books?id=YRCWtf_d5jgC&lpg=PA339&dq=kenkun%20shrine&lr&pg=PA339#v=onepage&q=kenkun%20shrine&f=true | doi = | id = | isbn =978-0-8048-3341-7 }}</ref>
